{"parse":{"title":"head","pageid":214,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|-head|Head}}\n==English==\n{{wp|<dab>}}\n{{picdic\n|image=Human head and brain diagram.svg\n|width=310\n|labels=\n{{picdiclabel|en|align=left|pcolor=black|fontsize=12|x=150|y=3|skull}}\n{{picdiclabel|en|align=left|pcolor=black|fontsize=18|x=170|y=90|brain}}\n{{picdiclabel|en|align=left|pcolor=black|fontsize=12|x=80|y=160|eye}}\n{{picdiclabel|en|align=left|pcolor=black|fontsize=12|x=15|y=190|nose}}\n{{picdiclabel|en|align=left|pcolor=black|fontsize=12|x=50|y=230|mouth}}\n{{picdiclabel|en|align=left|pcolor=black|fontsize=12|x=35|y=285|chin}}\n{{picdiclabel|en|align=left|pcolor=black|fontsize=12|x=90|y=270|jaw}}\n{{picdiclabel|en|align=left|pcolor=black|fontsize=12|x=175|y=205|ear}}\n{{picdiclabel|en|align=left|pcolor=black|fontsize=12|x=120|y=140|temple}}\n{{picdiclabel|en|align=left|pcolor=black|fontsize=12|x=185|y=290|neck}}\n|detail1=Click on labels in the image\n|detail2=\n{{picdicimg|en|image=Human body features-nb.svg|link=body}}\n}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{enPR|hĕd}}, {{IPA|en|/hɛd/|a=RP,GA,CA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/hɛd/|/hɛːd/|a=Early Modern|ref2={{R:en:Dobson:1957|II|30|502}}}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-head.ogg|a=US}}\n** {{audio|en|en-uk-head.ogg|a=UK}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Back ache-head.wav|a=London}}\n* {{IPA|en|/hed/|a=AU,NZ}}\n* {{IPA|en|/hiːd/|a={{w|Northumbrian dialect|Northumbrian}}}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɛd|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|en|id=Q23640|:inh|enm:heed<id:head>|tree=1}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|efd}}, {{m|enm|had}}, {{m|enm|hafd}}, {{m|enm|heafd}}, {{m|enm|hed}}, {{m|enm|heed}}, {{m|enm|hefet}}, {{m|enm|heid}}, {{m|enm|het}}, {{m|enm|hevd}}, {{m|enm|heved}}, {{m|enm|hevid}}, {{m|enm|hiede}}, {{m|enm|hæfd}}, {{m|enm|hæfedd}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hēafod|t=head; top; leader; origin}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*haubud}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*haubudą|t=head}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*káput|t=head}}, from {{m|ine-pro|*kap-|t=head; bowl, cup|id=head}}. \n\nThe modern word comes from Old English oblique stem ''hēafd-''; the expected Modern English outcome for ''hēafod'' would be ''*heaved'' (similar to the Middle English word). {{doublet|en|cape|capo|caput|chef|chief|Howth}}.\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|heid|t=head}}, {{cog|yol|haade}}, {{m|yol|hade}}, {{m|yol|heade|t=head}}, {{cog|frr|Haur}}, {{m|frr|hood|t=head}}, {{cog|stq|Haud}}, {{m|stq|Hööft|t=head}}, {{cog|fy|haad|t=head}}, {{cog|gsw|Haupt|t=head}}, {{cog|nl|hoofd|t=head}}, {{cog|de|Haupt}}, {{m|de|Häupt|t=head}}, {{cog|wym|hiöet}}, {{m|wym|hiöt}}, {{m|wym|huöt}}, {{m|wym|huø̄t|t=head}}, {{cog|yi|הויפּט|t=head}}, {{cog|da|hode}}, {{m|da|hoved|t=head}}, {{cog|ovd|ovuð|t=head}}, {{cog|fo|høvd}}, {{m|fo|høvur|t=head}}, {{cog|is|höfuð|t=head}}, {{cog|gmq-jmk|huvu|t=head}}, {{cog|nb|hode}}, {{m|nb|hue|t=head}}, {{cog|nn|haud}}, {{m|nn|hauv}}, {{m|nn|hove}}, {{m|nn|hovu}}, {{m|nn|hovud}}, {{m|nn|hue}}, {{m|nn|huggu}}, {{m|nn|hugu}}, {{m|nn|hugud}}, {{m|nn|huvu}}, {{m|nn|huvud|t=head}}, {{cog|gmq-scy|huweð|t=head}}, {{cog|sv|hufvud}}, {{m|sv|hufwud}}, {{m|sv|huve}}, {{m|sv|huvud}}, {{m|sv|hövve|t=head}}, {{cog|gme-cgo|hoef|t=head}}, {{cog|got|𐌷𐌰𐌿𐌱𐌹𐌳}}, {{m|got|𐌷𐌰𐌿𐌱𐌹𐌸|t=head}}; also {{cog|ga,gd|cuach|t=bowl; dome (of head)}}, {{cog|cy|cawg|t=basin, bowl, vessel}}, {{cog|la|capud}}, {{m|la|capus}}, {{m|la|caput|t=head}}, {{cog|el|κεφάλι}}, {{m|el|κεφαλή|t=head}}, {{cog|ckb|کاپۆڵ|t=skull}}, {{cog|sa|कपाल|t=skull; bowl}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|en|'ead||UK|eye dialect}}\n* {{alter|en|heead||Yorkshire}}\n* {{alter|en|hed||archaic}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|~|+|*}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q23640}} {{lb|en|countable}} The part of the [[body]] of an animal or human which contains the [[brain]], [[mouth]]{{,}} and main [[sense]] [[organs]].\n#: {{syn|en|caput|pate|noggin<q:slang>|loaf|nut|noodle|bonce<q:UK slang>|Thesaurus:head}}\n#: {{ux|en|Be careful when you pet that dog on the '''head'''; it may bite.}}\n#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|page=175|chapter=8|passage=Afore we got to the shanty Colonel Applegate stuck his '''head''' out of the door. His temper had been getting raggeder all the time, and the sousing he got when he fell overboard had just about ripped what was left of it to ravellings.}}\n## {{lb|en|people}} {{n-g|To do with heads.}}\n### [[mental|Mental]] or [[emotional]] [[aptitude]] or [[skill]].\n###: {{syn|en|mind}}\n###: {{ux|en|The company is looking for people with good '''heads''' for business.}}\n###: {{ux|en|He has no '''head''' for heights.}}\n###: {{ux|en|It's all about having a good '''head''' on your shoulders.}}\n###* {{quote-book|en|year=1951|author={{w|John Wyndham}}|title={{w|The Day of the Triffids}}|publisher=Penguin Books|year_published=1954|location=Harmondsworth|page=25|passage=And each of a succession of teachers who tried to show me that mathematical answers were derived logically and not through some form of esoteric inspiration was forced to give up with the assurance that I had no '''head''' for figures. My father 'would read my school reports with a gloom which in other respects they scarcely warranted. His mind worked, I think, this way: no '''head''' for figures = no idea of finance = no money.}}\n### {{lb|en|figurative|metonymy}} [[mind|Mind]]; one's own [[thought]]s.\n###: {{ux|en|This song keeps going through my '''head'''.}}\n###* {{quote-book|en|year=1935|author=w:George Goodchild|title=Death on the Centre Court|chapter=1\n|passage=“Anthea hasn't a notion in her '''head''' but to vamp a lot of silly mugwumps. She's set her heart on that tennis bloke{{...}}whom the papers are making such a fuss about.”}}\n### A [[headache]]; especially one resulting from [[intoxication]].\n###* {{RQ:Kipling Plain Tales|chapter=Thrown Away|page=15|passage=He found whist, and gymkhanas, and things of that kind (meant to amuse one after office) good; but he took them seriously, too, just as seriously as he took the “'''head'''” that followed after drink.}}\n###* {{quote-book|en|year=1913|author={{w|Norman Lindsay}}|title={{w|A Curate in Bohemia (novel)|A Curate in Bohemia}}|publisher=N.S.W. Bookstall Co.|year_published=1932|location=Sydney|page=117|passage=\"Now you ''have'' done it, Spuds,\" said Cripps. \"You'll have an awful '''head''' on you tomorrow.\"}}\n###* {{RQ:Doyle Land of Mist|passage=\"Mornin', Tom,\" he said in a husky voice. Then as the wife left the room: \"Got a drop of Scotch about? I've a '''head''' on me this morning.\"}}\n### A [[headdress]]; a covering for the head.\n###: {{co|en|a laced '''head'''}}\n###: {{co|en|a '''head''' of hair}}\n### {{lb|en|figurative|metonymy}} An individual [[person]].\n###: {{ux|en|Admission is three dollars a '''head'''.}}\n###* {{RQ:Fielding Tom Jones|volume=III|book=VIII|chapter=VII|pages=196–197|pageref=197|passage={{...}} but here we are obliged to diſcloſe ſome Maxims, which Publicans hold to be the grand Myſteries of their Trade. {{...}} And, laſtly, if any of their Gueſts call but for little, to make them pay a double Price for every Thing they have&#8239;; ſo that the Amount by the '''Head''' may be much the ſame.}}\n## {{lb|en|animals}} {{n-g|To do with heads.}}\n### {{senseid|en|measure for one animal}} {{lb|en|plural '''head'''}} A single [[animal]]; {{n-g|[[w:Measure word|measure word]] for [[livestock]] and [[game]]}}.\n###: {{co|en|200 '''head''' of cattle and 50 '''head''' of horses}}\n### The population of [[game]].\n###: {{ux|en|We have a heavy '''head''' of deer this year.}}\n### The [[antler]]s of a [[deer]].\n# {{senseid|en|topmost or foremost part}} {{lb|en|countable}} The [[topmost]], [[foremost]]{{,}} or [[leading]] part.\n#: {{ant|en|base|bottom|underside|foot|tail}}\n#: {{ux|en|What does it say at the '''head''' of the page?}}\n#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|page=243|chapter=10|passage=Men that I knew around Wapatomac didn't wear high, shiny plug hats, nor yeller spring overcoats, nor carry canes with ivory '''heads''' as big as a catboat's anchor, as you might say.}}\n## The end of a [[table]].\n### The end of a [[rectangular]] table furthest from the [[entrance]]; traditionally considered a [[seat]] of [[honor]].\n###: {{ux|en|During meetings, the supervisor usually sits at the '''head''' of the table.}}\n### {{lb|en|billiards}} The end of a [[pool]] table opposite the end where the balls have been [[rack]]ed.\n## {{lb|en|countable}} The [[principal]] [[operative]] part of a machine, tool or fastener.\n### The end of a [[hammer]], [[axe]], [[golf club]]{{,}} or similar [[implement]] used for striking other objects.\n### The end of a [[nail]], [[screw]], [[bolt]]{{,}} or similar [[fastener]] which is opposite the [[point]]; usually [[blunt]] and relatively [[wide]]. \n###: {{ant|en|point|tip}}\n###: {{ux|en|Hit the nail on the '''head'''!}}\n### {{lb|en|countable|metalworking|construction|of a rivet}}: \n#### The larger-diameter end of an unused [[rivet]], properly the [[factory head]] or ambiguously the [[shop head]], as opposed to the [[bucktail]] which is passed through the items to be fastened and then [[upset#Verb|upset]] into an appropriate shape, generally pancake-shaped for a solid rivet or doughnut-shaped for a [[blind rivet]], called the [[field head]] or ambiguously the [[shop head]].\n#### Either, or in plural both, ends of a used rivet, the factory head and the field head.\n### The [[sharp]] end of an [[arrow]], [[spear]]{{,}} or [[pointer]].\n###: {{ux|en|The '''head''' of the compass needle is pointing due north.}}\n### {{lb|en|lacrosse}} The top part of a [[lacrosse stick]] that holds the [[ball]].\n### {{lb|en|music}} A [[drum head]], the [[membrane]] which is hit to produce [[sound]].\n###: {{ux|en|Tap the '''head''' of the drum for this roll.}}\n### A [[machine]] element which reads or writes [[electromagnetic]] signals to or from a storage medium.\n###: {{ux|en|The '''heads''' of your tape player need to be cleaned.}}\n### {{lb|en|computing}} The part of a [[disk drive]] responsible for reading and writing data.\n### {{lb|en|automotive}} The [[cylinder head]], a platform above the [[cylinder]]s in an [[internal combustion engine]], containing the [[valve]]s and [[spark plug]]s.\n### {{lb|en|machining}} A milling head, a part of a {{l|en|milling machine}} that houses the {{l|en|spindle}}.\n## {{lb|en|uncountable|countable}} The [[foam]] that forms on top of [[beer]] or other [[carbonated]] [[beverage]]s.\n##: {{ux|en|Pour me a fresh beer; this one has no '''head'''.}}\n##: {{ux|en|He never learned how to pour a glass of beer so it didn't have too much '''head'''.}}\n## {{senseid|en|engineering}} {{lb|en|engineering}} The end cap of a cylindrically-shaped [[pressure vessel]].\n## {{senseid|en|coopering}} {{lb|en|coopering}} The end cap of a [[cask]] or other [[barrel]].\n##: {{syn|en|barrelhead}}\n## {{lb|en|geology}} The uppermost part of a [[valley]].\n##* {{quote-book\n|en\n|year=1912\n|author=w:Robert Sterling Clark; w:Arthur de Carle Sowerby\n|title=Through Shên-kan: The Account of the Clark Expedition in North China, 1908-9.\n|url=https://archive.org/details/b29353002/\n|publisher=w:T. Fisher Unwin\n|OCLC=4711508\n|page=122\n|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/b29353002/page/n249/\n|text=A deep bed of this red sandstone occurs at the '''head''' of the Yen Shui valley, a few miles south of Ching-pien {{transterm|zh|靖邊}}.}}\n## {{lb|en|British|geology}} Deposits near the top of a [[geological]] [[succession]].\n## {{lb|en|journalism}} {{ellipsis of|en|headline}}.\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1968|author=Earl English; Clarence Hach|title=Scholastic Journalism|page=166\n|passage=The content of a headline over a news story should be taken from the lead of the story. {{...}} The '''head''' should give the same impression as the body of the story.}}\n## {{lb|en|medicine}} The end of an [[abscess]] where [[pus]] collects.\n## {{lb|en|music}} The [[headstock]] of a [[guitar]].\n## {{lb|en|nautical}} A leading component.\n### The [[top]] edge of a [[sail]].\n### The [[bow]] of a vessel.\n## {{lb|en|British}} A [[headland]].\n## A [[title]] or [[heading]] in a [[book]] or other [[document]].\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1807|author=George Burnett|title=Specimens of English Prose Writers|page=351\n|passage=In this repositary, the phenomena of nature are ranged under three principal '''heads'''.}}\n# {{senseid|en|leader}} {{lb|en|social|countable|metonymy}} A [[leader]] or [[expert]].\n#: {{syn|en|boss|chief|leader}}\n#: {{ant|en|subordinate}}\n#: {{ux|en|I'd like to speak to the '''head''' of the department.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Police arrested the '''head''' of the gang in a raid last night.}}\n#: {{ux|en|He's (the) '''head''' of a project here.}}\n#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|chapter=7|passage=“I don't know how you and the ‘'''head''',’ as you call him, will get on, but I do know that if you call my duds a ‘livery’ again there'll be trouble. It's bad enough to go around togged out like a life saver on a drill day, but I can stand that 'cause I'm paid for it. What I won't stand is to have them togs called a livery.{{...}}”}}\n## The [[place]] of [[honor]] or [[command]]; the most [[important]] or [[foremost]] position; the [[front]].\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1708|author=w:Joseph Addison|title=The present state of the war, and the necessity of an augmentation, consider'd|url=http://name.umdl.umich.edu/004834471.0001.000|page=33|text=We saw the last Campaign that an Army of Fourscore Thousand of the best Troops in ''Europe'', with the Duke of ''Marlborough'' at the '''Head''' of them, cou'd do nothing against an Enemy that were too numerous to be assaulted in their Camps, or attack'd in their Strong Holds.}}\n## {{lb|en|UK|Ireland|metonymy}} A [[headteacher]].\n##: {{syn|en|headmaster|headmistress|principal<q:US>}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|date=June 24 1992|author=w:Edwina Currie|journal=Diary\n|passage=At 4pm, the phone [[go|went]]. It was {{w|The Sun}}: 'We hear your daughter's been expelled for cheating at her school exams...' / She'd made a remark to a friend at the end of the German exam and had been [[pull up|pulled up]] for talking. / As they left the exam room, she muttered that the teacher was a '[[twat]]'. He heard and [[flip]]ped{{mdash}}a pretty stupid thing to do, knowing the kids were tired and tense after exams. Instead of dropping it, the teacher complained to the '''Head''' and Deb was [[carpet]]ed.}}\n##: {{ux|en|I was called into the '''head''''s office to discuss my behaviour.}}\n## {{lb|en|music|slang|figurative|metonymy}} A person with an extensive knowledge of [[hip hop]].\n##: {{ux|en|Only true '''heads''' know this.}}\n## {{lb|en|slang|AAVE}} An [[old head]].\n# A significant or important part.\n## A beginning or end, a protuberance.\n### The [[source]] of a [[river]]; the end of a [[lake]] where a river flows into it.\n###: {{ux|en|The expedition followed the river all the way to the '''head'''.}}\n### {{senseid|en|capitulum}} A clump of [[seed]]s, [[leave]]s or [[flower]]s; a [[capitulum]].\n###: {{ux|en|Give me a '''head''' of lettuce.}}\n###* {{quote-journal|en|year=2013|month=May-June|author=David Van Tassel; Lee DeHaan|magazine=w:American Scientist|title=Wild Plants to the Rescue|url=http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/2013/3/wild-plants-to-the-rescue|volume=101|issue=3|passage=Plant breeding is always a numbers game.{{...}}The wild species we use are rich in genetic variation,&nbsp;{{...}}. In addition, we are looking for rare alleles, so the more plants we try, the better. These rarities may be new mutations, or they can be existing ones that are neutral—or are even selected against—in a wild population. A good example is mutations that disrupt seed dispersal, leaving the seeds on the '''heads''' long after they are ripe.|accessdate=12 August 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814191107/http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/2013/3/wild-plants-to-the-rescue|archivedate=14 August 2013}}\n#### {{senseid|en|grain}} An [[ear]] of [[wheat]], [[barley]], or other small [[cereal]].\n#### The leafy top part of a tree.\n### {{lb|en|anatomy}} The rounded part of a bone fitting into a depression in another bone to form a ball-and-socket [[joint]].\n### {{senseid|en|toilet of a ship}} {{lb|en|nautical}} The [[toilet]] of a [[ship]].\n###: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:toilet|Thesaurus:bathroom}}\n###: {{ux|en|I've got to go to the '''head'''.}}\n### {{lb|en|in the plural}} Tiles laid at the eaves of a house.\n###* '''1875''', {{w|Edward H. Knight}}, Knight's American Mechanical Dictionary, vol. II, [https://books.google.com/books?id=UXJHAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1086 page 1086]\n###*: '''Heads.''' (''Roofing.'') Tiles which are laid at the eaves of a house\n## A component.\n### {{lb|en|jazz}} The principal [[melody]] or [[theme]] of a piece.\n### {{senseid|en|core of phrase, in linguistics}} {{lb|en|linguistics}} A [[morpheme]] that determines the category of a [[compound]] or the word that determines the [[syntactic]] type of the [[phrase]] of which it is a member.\n###: {{hol|en|phrase<id:grammar>}}\n###* {{quote-book |en |year=2022 |author=Rodney Huddleston, Geoffrey K. Pullum, Brett Reynolds |authorlink=Geoffrey K. Pullum |title=A Student's Introduction to English Grammar |edition=2nd |publisher=Cambridge University Press |page=xvi |passage=Linguists will see that we reject some assumptions quite widely held in twentieth-century generative linguistics. The differences are sharp and explicit enough that they should provide grounds for discussion without causing confusion. For example, we do not believe subordinators (‘complementizers’) or coordinators (‘conjunctions’) are '''heads''', and we treat ''every day'' as a noun phrase headed by ''day'' rather than a determinative phrase headed by ''every''. {{...}} That does not mean we are legislating a theoretical view: it is always possible to stop and ask whether certain facts about syntax are better explained under one theoretical conception rather than another.}}\n### {{lb|en|chemistry}} The first [[fraction]] of a [[distillation]] run, having a low [[boiling point]].\n###: {{syn|en|foreshot}}\n###: {{cot|en|heart|tail}}\n# [[headway|Headway]]; [[progress]].\n#: {{ux|en|We are having a difficult time making '''head''' against this wind.}}\n# Topic; [[subject]].\n#: {{ux|en|We will consider performance issues under the '''head''' of future improvements.}}\n# {{lb|en|only|_|in the singular}} [[denouement|Denouement]]; [[crisis]].\n#: {{ux|en|These issues are going to come to a '''head''' today.}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Richard 2|V|i|page=41|passage=''Northumberland,'' thou Ladder wherewithall / The mounting ''Bullingbrooke'' aſcends my Throne, / The time ſhall not be many houres of age, / More then it is, ere foule ſinne, gathering '''head,''' / Shall breake into corruption {{...}}}}\n#* '''1712''' October 18, anonymous letter in ''[[w:The Spectator (1711)|The Spectator]]'', edited by {{w|Joseph Addison}}, no. 513, collected in ''The Works of the Late Right Honorable Joseph Addison, Esq'', Birmingham: {{w|John Baskerville}}, published 1761, volume IV, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZutWAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA10 page 10]:\n#*: The indiſpoſition which has long hung upon me, is at laſt grown to ſuch an '''head''', that it muſt quickly make an end of me, or of itſelf.\n# {{senseid|en|pressure and energy in fluid dynamics}} {{lb|en|fluid dynamics}} Pressure and energy.\n## {{lb|en|uncountable|countable}} A buildup of [[fluid]] [[pressure]], often quantified as [[pressure head]].\n##: {{hypo|en|head of steam|w:hydraulic head<!--WP until WT-->}}\n##: {{ux|en|Let the engine build up a good '''head''' of steam.}}\n##: {{ux|en|How much '''head''' do you have at the Glens Falls feeder dam?}}\n## The difference in [[elevation]] between two points in a [[column]] of fluid, and the resulting [[pressure]] of the fluid at the lower point.\n## More generally, [[energy]] in a mass of fluid divided by its [[weight]].\n# {{lb|en|slang|vulgar|uncountable}} [[fellatio|Fellatio]] or [[cunnilingus]]; [[oral sex]].\n#: {{syn|en|blowjob|Thesaurus:oral sex}}\n#: {{ux|en|She gave great '''head'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Danny got '''head''' last night.}}\n# {{lb|en|slang}} The [[glans penis]].\n# {{lb|en|slang|countable}} A heavy or [[habitual]] user of [[illicit]] [[drug]]s.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1936|author=Lee Duncan|title=Over The Wall|publisher=Dutton\n|passage=Then I saw the more advanced narcotic addicts, who shot unbelievable doses of powerful heroin in the main line – the vein of their arms; the hysien users; chloroform sniffers, who belonged to the riff-raff element of the dope chippeys, who mingled freely with others of their kind; canned heat stiffs, paragoric hounds, laudanum fiends, and last but not least, the veronal '''heads'''.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1968|author=Fred Davis|coauthors=Laura Munoz|title=Heads and freaks: patterns and meanings of drug use among hippies|journal=Journal of Health and Social Behavior|volume=9|issue=2|page=156–64|passage=The term, \"'''head''',\" is, of course, not new with hippies. It has a long history among drug users generally, for whom it signified a regular, experienced user of any illegal drug—e.g., pot \"head,\" meth \"head,\" smack (heroin) \"head.\"}}\n#* {{RQ:Torgoff Can't Find My Way Home|page=177|passage=The hutch now looks like a “Turkish bath,” and the '''heads''' have their arms around one another, passing the pipe and snapping their fingers as they sing Smokey Robinson's “Tracks of My Tears” into the night.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Power; armed force.\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 6-1|I|iv|page=100|passage=My lord, my lord, the French have gathered '''head''':}}\n\n=====Gallery=====\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Human head and brain diagram.svg|The human '''head'''\nImage:Milk thistle flowerhead.jpg|A flower '''head'''\nImage:Ikeya-zhang-comet-by-rhemann.png|'''Head''' of a comet\nImage:MUO GTMO 2003.png|'''Head''' of the line\nImage:Arrow and spear heads - from-DC1.jpg|Arrow and spear '''heads'''\nImage:Head of a hammer.jpg|'''Head''' of a hammer\nImage:Meetpunt.jpg|'''Head''' of a metal spike\nImage:Hip_replacement_Image_3684-PH.jpg|'''Head''' of the hip bone\nImage:MV Doulos in Keelung-2.jpg|'''Head''' of a ship\nImage:Mainsail-edges.png|'''Head''' of a sail\nImage:Diffuser Head.jpg|'''Head''' of a pressurized cylinder\nImage:Malossi 70cc Morini cylinder head.jpg|'''Head''' of a two-stroke engine\nImage:Hydraulic head.PNG|Hydraulic '''head''' between two points\nImage:Citizen W1D-9364 - read write head-4005.jpg|A read-write '''head'''\nImage:Fender Telecaster Head.jpg|'''Head''' of a guitar\nImage:Drumhead.jpg|'''Head''' of a drum\n</gallery>\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|en|title=Terms derived from ''head'' (noun)<!-- \"godhead\" and \"maidenhead\" are not from the Noun \"head\" but from the unrelated affix \"-head\" which is related to \"-hood\" -->|acidhead\n|addlehead\n|ahead|Indented Head\n|air-head\n|airhead\n|angels-dancing-on-the-head-of-a-pin,angels dancing on the head of a pin\n|applehead\n|arrow-head,arrowhead|heads of terms\n|arsehead\n|asshead\n|Asaro's head\n|axe head,axhead\n|backhead\n|backheader|ball-head onion|take something to the head\n|Badger Head\n|bagel head|P-Head\n|bakehead\n|baldhead,bald head\n|Ballast Head|Asaro head|give someone their head|hand someone their head|hand someone their head on a plate|hand someone their head on a platter|planes of the head|put into one's own head|stink head\n|ballhead\n|balloon head\n|bandhead\n|bang one's head against a brick wall\n|bang some heads together\n|Bankhead|head of the table|head-up|roof over the head|cooler heads prevailed|saner heads prevail|saner heads prevailed|saner heads will prevail\n|barrel-head,barrel head\n|Barwon Heads\n|bash someone's head\n|Bayonet Head\n|bayhead|Bay Head\n|beach head,beachhead,beach-head\n|Beachy Head|baby's head|green head|young head\n|beak-head|arse over head|get one's head out of the gutter|have a turtle's head|head boom|head-mold-shot|he