 pain\n|sheepshead\n|sheep's head\n|sherm head\n|sherm-head\n|Shoalhaven Heads\n|shockhead\n|shop head\n|short head\n|short-head seahorse\n|shovelhead\n|shower head\n|showerhead\n|shut one's head\n|sidehead\n|sillyhead\n|silverhead\n|Skennars Head\n|skinhead\n|sled head\n|sledhead\n|sled-head\n|sleepyhead,sleepy head\n|slickhead\n|slimehead\n|sliphead\n|slopehead\n|slow head\n|sluthead\n|smackhead\n|smash someone's head\n|smeghead\n|smh one's head\n|snakehead\n|snake's-head\n|snakeshead\n|snake's head\n|snaphead\n|snapperhead\n|snap someone's head off\n|snothead\n|softhead\n|softheaded\n|soft in the head\n|sorehead\n|sound head\n|South Bird's Head\n|spear-head\n|spearhead\n|spermhead\n|spinyhead\n|Spithead\n|split head\n|spreadhead\n|springhead\n|sprinkler head\n|spud head\n|squarehead\n|stagehead\n|stairhead\n|stakehead\n|standing on one's head\n|stand on one's head\n|steelhead\n|steering head\n|stemhead\n|stick one's head in the sand\n|Stony Head\n|strawhead\n|stupid-head\n|subhead\n|subheading\n|suedehead\n|superhead\n|Swansea Heads\n|swelled head\n|swellhead\n|table head\n|tailhead\n|take it into one's head\n|take someone's head off\n|talking head\n|talk over someone's head\n|talk someone's head off\n|tech head\n|tech-head\n|tetched in the head\n|the fish rots from the head\n|The Head\n|the sky will fall on your head\n|thickhead\n|thickheaded\n|think with one's little head\n|think with one's other head\n|thornhead\n|thunderhead\n|tighthead\n|tight-head\n|tight head\n|timberhead\n|tithead\n|too much bed makes a dull head\n|Torx head\n|touched in the head\n|towelhead\n|tow-head\n|towhead\n|Town Head,Townhead\n|trail head\n|trailhead\n|Trevose Head\n|trundlehead\n|Tully Heads\n|tuning head\n|Turk's head,turk's head\n|turn heads\n|turnip head\n|turn on its head\n|turn someone's head\n|Tuross Head\n|turret head\n|turtlehead\n|Tweed Heads\n|Tweed Heads South\n|Tweed Heads West\n|two heads are better than one\n|typehead\n|underhead\n|uneasy lies the head that wears a crown\n|unhead\n|upside the head\n|use one's head\n|veg-head\n|wankhead\n|warhead\n|Wasdale Head\n|waterhead\n|Wearhead\n|weedhead\n|weeniehead\n|wellhead\n|West Bird's Head\n|West Quoddy Head\n|wethead\n|wet the baby's head\n|Whitehead\n|whitehead\n|Whiteheads Creek\n|wig head\n|windmills in one's head\n|winghead\n|wirehead\n|wisehead\n|wise head on young shoulders\n|with one's head held high\n|wolf's head\n|woodenhead\n|Woody Head\n|woolhead\n|woolly-head\n|would lose one's head if it wasn't attached\n|would lose one's head if it wasn't bolted on\n|would lose one's head if it wasn't glued on\n|would lose one's head if it wasn't screwed on\n|would lose one's head if it wasn't stuck on\n|would lose one's head if it wasn't tied on\n|would lose one's head if it weren't attached\n|wrap one's head around\n|write head\n|wronghead\n|wrongheaded\n|yellowhead\n|you can't put an old head on young shoulders\n|you can't put a wise head on young shoulders\n|Young Nick's Head\n|your head\n|ziphead\n|zipperhead\n}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|ja|ヘッド|tr=heddo|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|srn|ede}}\n** {{desc|djk|ede}}\n** {{desc|srm|hédi}}\n* {{desc|tpi|het}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{see translation subpage|Noun}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{en-adj|-}}\n\n# Of, relating to, or intended for the head.\n#: {{syn|es|cephalic|capital}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top-see|of, relating to, or intended for the head|cephalic|capital}}\n* Bulgarian: {{no equivalent translation|bg}} {{t|bg|[[на]] [[глава]]}}, {{t|bg|[[за]][[глава]]}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|hoofd|n}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|kapa}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[pää]]-}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Kopf|alt=Kopf-}}, {{qualifier|dated}} {{t+|de|Haupt|alt=Haupt-}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|κεφαλικός}}\n* Gujarati: {{t|gu|માથુ}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|सिर|tr=}}, {{t+|hi|मस्तक|tr=}}\n* Italian: {{t-check|it|[[di]] [[testa]]}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|頭の|tr=あたまの, atama no}}\n* Kabuverdianu: {{t|kea|kabesa}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|cacumen}}, {{t+|la|caput}}\n* Naga:\n*: Khiamniungan Naga: {{t|kix|khèu}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|hode-}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|головно́й}}\n* Sanskrit: {{t+|sa|ककुद्|tr=kakud}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|hlavový}}\n* Spanish: {{t|es|[[de]] [[cabeza]]}}\n* Swedish: ''compounds with'' {{t+check|sv|huvud}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|baş}}, {{t+|tr|kafa}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|be in command}} {{lb|en|transitive}} To be in command of. (See also {{m|en|head up}}.)\n#: {{ux|en|Who '''heads''' the board of trustees?}}\n#: {{ux|en|to '''head''' an army, an expedition, or a riot}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To come at the beginning or front of; to [[commence]].\n#: {{ux|en|A group of clowns '''headed''' the procession.}}\n#: {{ux|en|The most important items '''headed''' the list.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1943|month=November and December|author=G. T. Porter|title=The Lines Behind the Lines in Burma|journal=Railway Magazine|page=325|text=When it arrived, the train was '''headed''' by a \"K\" class 4-6-0 wood-burning locomotive, and a water-tank wagon next to the tender was immediately besieged by women and girls, clad in their picturesque national costume, all with empty kerosene tins for water, a scene which was re-enacted at each stop down the line.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2018|author=James Lambert|title=Setting the Record Straight: An In-depth Examination of ''Hobson-Jobson''|journal=International Journal of Lexicography|volume=31|issue=4|doi=https://doi.org/10.1093/ijl/ecy010|page=491|text=The citations are set in smaller font, start on a new indented line and are '''headed''' with a date.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To strike with the head\n#: {{co|en|to '''head''' the ball}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To move in a specified [[direction]].\n#: {{syn|en|seek|bear}}\n#: {{ux|en|We are going to '''head''' up North for our holiday.}}\n#: {{ux|en|We will [['''head''' off]] tomorrow.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Next holiday we will '''head out''' West, or '''head to''' Chicago.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Right now I need to '''head''' into town to do some shopping.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I'm fed up working for a boss. I'm going to '''head out''' on my own, set up my own business.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Where does the train '''head''' to?}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1960|month=December|author=Voyageur|title=The Mountain Railways of the Bernese Oberland|journal=Trains Illustrated|page=752|text=To the left towers the Jungfrau, with the train '''heading''' directly towards it.}}\n# {{lb|en|fishing|transitive}} To [[remove]] the head from (a fish).\n#: {{cot|en|bone#Verb|debone#Verb|gut#Verb|scale#Verb|descale#Verb}}\n#: {{nearsyn|en|behead#Verb|dehead#Verb}}\n#: {{ux|en|The salmon are first '''headed''' and then scaled.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[originate]]; to [[spring]]; to have its course, as a river.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1775|author=[[w:James Adair (historian)|James Adair]]|title=The History of the American Indians|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofamerica01adai/page/223/mode/1up|page=223\n|passage=a broad purling river, that '''heads''' in the great blue ridge of mountains,}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1934|author=w:Henry G. Lamond|title=An Aviary on the Plains|publisher=Angus and Robertson|location=Sydney|page=156|passage=The Templeton '''heads''' in the Cloncurry ranges[.]}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To form a head.\n#: {{ux|en|This kind of cabbage '''heads''' early.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Anne Raver|chapter=Gandhi Gardening|title=Deep in the Green: An Exploration of Country Pleasures|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Alfred A. Knopf|year=1995|isbn=978-0-307-82840-8|passage=To be honest, this hasn't been my Garden of Eden year. {{...}} The lettuce turned bitter and bolted. The Green Comet broccoli was good, but my coveted Romanescos never '''headed''' up.}}\n# {{senseid|en|form a head on (hardware)}} {{lb|en|transitive|of hardware}} To form a head (on or to); to fit or furnish (something) with a head.\n#: {{ux|en|to '''head''' a nail}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cut off the top of; to lop off.\n#: {{ux|en|to '''head''' trees}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[behead]]; to [[decapitate]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1822|author=[[w:Allan Cunningham (author)|Allan Cunningham]]|chapter=[[s:Traditional Tales of the English and Scottish Peasantry/Ezra Peden|Ezra Peden]]|title=Traditional Tales of the English and Scottish Peasantry|pageurl=https://archive.org/stream/traditionaltales01cunn#page/n55/mode/2up|volume=1|page=37\n|passage=I tell thee, man of God, the uncharitableness of the sect to which thou pertainest has thronged the land of punishment as much as those who '''headed''', and hanged, and stabbed, and shot, and tortured.}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Measure|2|1|passage=If you '''head''', and hang all that offend that way<br>but for ten yeare together; you'll be glad to giue out a<br>Commission for more heads}}\n# To go in front of.\n#: {{ux|en|to '''head''' a drove of cattle}}\n#: {{ux|en|to '''head''' a person}}\n# To get in the front of, so as to hinder or stop; to oppose.\n#: {{ux|en|The wind '''headed''' the ship and made progress difficult.}}\n# {{lb|en|by extension}} To [[check]] or [[restrain]].\n# To set on the head.\n#: {{ux|en|to '''head''' a cask}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|behead\n|double-head\n|head for the hills\n|head off\n|where the puck is heading\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|en|ahead}}\n* {{l|en|knucklehead}}\n* {{l|en|railhead}}\n* {{l|en|smackhead}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top-see|to be in command of|direct|lead}}\n* Basque: {{t|eu|zuzendu}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|узнача́льваць|impf}}, {{t|be|ачо́льваць|impf}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|ren}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|ръководя}}, {{t|bg|оглавявам|impf}}, {{t|bg|оглавя|pf}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|comandar}}, {{t+|ca|dirigir}}, {{t+|ca|encapçalar}}, {{t+|ca|liderar}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|leiden}}, {{t+|nl|aanvoeren}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|komandi}}, {{t|eo|konduki}}, {{t|eo|gvidi}}, {{t|eo|ĉefi}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|johtaa}}, {{t+|fi|komentaa}} {{qualifier|military}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|commander}}, {{t+|fr|diriger}}, {{t+|fr|chapeauter}}\n* German: {{t+|de|führen}}, {{t+|de|leiten}}, {{t+|de|anführen}}, {{t|de|[[die]] [[Leitung]] [[innehaben]]}}, {{t|de|[[die]] [[Führung]] [[innehaben]]}}, {{t|de|[[an]] [[der]] [[Spitze]] [[stehen]]}}\n* Guarani:\n*: Paraguayan Guarani: {{t-check|gug|myakã}}\n* Hebrew: {{t|he|עמד בראש|tr=amad b’rosh}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|प्रमुख|m}}, {{t+|hi|मुख्य}}, {{t+|hi|मुखिया|m}}, {{t+|hi|प्रधान|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|irányít}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|leiða}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|pimpin|alt=memimpin}}\n* Interlingua: {{t|ia|commandar}}, {{t|ia|diriger}}, {{t|ia|leaderar}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|指導する|tr=しどうする, shidō-suru}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{t+|kmr|birêvebirin}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|lede}}, {{t+|nb|anføre}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|اداره کردن|tr=edâre kardan}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|kierować}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|comandar}}, {{t+|pt|dirigir}}, {{t+|pt|liderar}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|comanda}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|возглавля́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|возгла́вить|pf}}, {{t+|ru|руководи́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|главе́нствовать|impf}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|viesť}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|encabezar}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|leda}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|очо́лювати|impf}}, {{t|uk|очо́лити|pf}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to come at the beginning of; to commence}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|оглавявам|impf}}, {{t|bg|оглавя|pf}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|en tête|alt=être en tête de}}, {{t+|fr|à la tête de|alt=être à la tête de}}\n* German: {{t+|de|anführen}}, {{t|de|[[vorangehen]]}}, {{t|de|[[sich]] [[an]] [[der]] [[Spitze]] [[befinden]]}}, {{t|de|[[die]] [[Spitze]] [[bilden]]}}, {{t|de|[[an]] [[der]] [[Spitze]] [[stehen]]}}, {{t|de|[[sich]] [[ganz]] [[vorne]] [[befinden]]}}\n* Hungarian: {{t|hu|[[él#Hungarian: forefront|élen/élén]] [[áll]]}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|lede}}, {{t+|nb|anføre}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to strike with the head}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|[[удрям]] [[с]] [[глава]]|impf}}, {{t|bg|[[у